00:01:46.100 --> 00:01:47.670
- Good afternoon, and welcome

00:01:47.670 --> 00:01:50.220
to this CARTA symposium on hunting.

00:01:50.220 --> 00:01:51.480
My name is Pascal Gagneux.

00:01:51.480 --> 00:01:53.410
I'm the Associate Director of CARTA.

00:01:54.280 --> 00:01:57.280
Among the oldest questions
humans have asked themselves are,

00:01:58.140 --> 00:02:00.680
who are we, what are we doing here,

00:02:01.740 --> 00:02:04.680
where did we come from,
how did we get here,

00:02:05.620 --> 00:02:07.590
and where are we going.

00:02:07.590 --> 00:02:10.440
Anthropogeny focuses on
two of these questions,

00:02:10.440 --> 00:02:14.090
namely, where did we come
from, and how did we get here.

00:02:16.600 --> 00:02:19.330
It brings together a
variety of disciplines,

00:02:19.330 --> 00:02:21.840
because we believe that
understanding human origins

00:02:21.840 --> 00:02:23.880
is only possible at the intersection

00:02:23.880 --> 00:02:26.810
between the social and
the natural sciences,

00:02:26.810 --> 00:02:30.950
with help from computing
sciences and various disciplines.

00:02:30.950 --> 00:02:33.730
It's a question that's
so big that no single

00:02:33.730 --> 00:02:35.610
discipline will be able to answer it.

