00:05:28.280 --> 00:05:31.200
It's wonderful to have a symposium here,

00:05:31.200 --> 00:05:35.580
on a problem that is a
wonderful meld of interests,

00:05:35.580 --> 00:05:37.990
if you happen to be
someone who is interested

00:05:37.990 --> 00:05:41.230
in both chimpanzees and in humans.

00:05:41.230 --> 00:05:46.230
What we're dealing with here is ultimately

00:05:46.580 --> 00:05:49.590
a hypothesis that has been of huge impact,

00:05:49.590 --> 00:05:53.980
in terms of anthropology
in general, actually.

00:05:55.210 --> 00:05:57.650
When Washburn and Lancaster produced this,

00:05:57.650 --> 00:06:01.010
this notion that the intellect, interests,

00:06:01.010 --> 00:06:02.770
emotions and basic social life

00:06:02.770 --> 00:06:06.020
all are evolutionary products
of the hunting adaptation,

00:06:06.020 --> 00:06:08.180
that may have been a slight exaggeration,

00:06:08.180 --> 00:06:10.000
but it nevertheless remains true today

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:12.546
that a tremendous amount
of the way in which

00:06:12.546 --> 00:06:17.080
our own adaptations have evolved are seen

00:06:17.080 --> 00:06:21.060
as going on through lives
of hunters and gatherers.

00:06:21.060 --> 00:06:23.490
And of course, hunters
and gatherers very much

00:06:23.490 --> 00:06:27.730
are thought of in terms
of the hunting adaptation.

00:06:27.730 --> 00:06:29.760
The particular time when this

00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:32.180
received bigger stimulus than any,

00:06:32.180 --> 00:06:35.300
perhaps, was on the occasion of the Man

00:06:35.300 --> 00:06:37.600
the Hunter symposium in Chicago,

00:06:37.600 --> 00:06:40.160
that led to a famous book.

00:06:40.160 --> 00:06:43.540
And it's worth noting that this had

00:06:43.540 --> 00:06:46.070
scholars all across anthropology,

00:06:46.070 --> 00:06:49.110
from archeologists and
biological anthropologists,

00:06:49.110 --> 00:06:52.150
to social anthropologists
like Marshall Sahlins there.

00:06:52.150 --> 00:06:55.470
And even though it
sounds appallingly sexist

00:06:55.470 --> 00:06:58.500
to think of man the hunter as being

00:06:58.500 --> 00:07:01.400
the origin of so many of our adaptations,

00:07:01.400 --> 00:07:05.550
it's worth remembering
that out of that symposium,

00:07:05.550 --> 00:07:08.170
came for the first time the appreciation

00:07:08.170 --> 00:07:10.850
that foraging by females might be,

00:07:10.850 --> 00:07:13.470
well, at least as important as hunting.

00:07:15.080 --> 00:07:20.080
So that was '68, '66, and it was happening

00:07:20.720 --> 00:07:23.890
at a time when people have
just started to realize

00:07:23.890 --> 00:07:26.140
that thanks to Jane Goodall's work

00:07:26.140 --> 00:07:28.000
starting in the early 1960s,

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:31.900
that chimpanzees,
astonishingly, were hunters

00:07:31.900 --> 00:07:34.500
in a somewhat human-like style.

00:07:34.500 --> 00:07:38.020
With the males being
more engaged in hunting,

00:07:38.020 --> 00:07:41.490
and all of these fascinating associated

00:07:41.490 --> 00:07:44.470
features such as food sharing.

00:07:45.424 --> 00:07:50.424
And the pattern of the
development of interest in hunting

00:07:50.960 --> 00:07:55.730
is therefore taken both chimps
and humans side by side,

00:07:55.730 --> 00:07:57.090
and you might think
that all the interesting

00:07:57.090 --> 00:07:59.370
questions have now been answered.

00:07:59.370 --> 00:08:00.940
But a few months ago,

00:08:01.900 --> 00:08:05.640
Jim Moore and Ian Gilby
were talking together

00:08:05.640 --> 00:08:08.090
about the fact that even such a question

00:08:08.090 --> 00:08:11.740
as why is it that chimpanzees
in some populations

00:08:11.740 --> 00:08:16.220
hunt a lot more than others,
had not really been answered.

00:08:16.220 --> 00:08:17.980
And out of their
conversations, they realized

00:08:17.980 --> 00:08:20.850
there were a whole slew of problems.

00:08:20.850 --> 00:08:25.850
What exactly is the reason
that chimps or humans hunt?

00:08:26.390 --> 00:08:28.180
And in both cases, we've got the question

00:08:28.180 --> 00:08:30.060
is it really for nutritional benefits,

00:08:30.060 --> 00:08:32.070
or are they showing off in some way.

00:08:32.070 --> 00:08:34.390
And by the way, if it
is nutritional benefits,

00:08:34.390 --> 00:08:36.480
what are the nutritional benefits?

00:08:36.480 --> 00:08:39.050
And are they consistent
in different contexts?

00:08:39.050 --> 00:08:42.270
It's still really an unresolved question.

00:08:42.270 --> 00:08:45.250
We still know rather
little about the degree

00:08:45.250 --> 00:08:48.890
to which hunting is beneficial
at the individual level,

00:08:48.890 --> 00:08:51.450
or how much cooperation is needed for it.

00:08:52.770 --> 00:08:55.560
Only recently has much attention

00:08:55.560 --> 00:08:58.370
been paid to hunting by females.

00:08:58.370 --> 00:09:00.920
So this core question for anthropology

00:09:00.920 --> 00:09:04.720
50 years ago still remains very much

00:09:06.320 --> 00:09:08.830
unexplored, or underexplored.

00:09:08.830 --> 00:09:10.480
And of course, it ultimately relates

00:09:10.480 --> 00:09:14.100
to the origins of human hunting.

00:09:14.100 --> 00:09:18.510
So the classic kind of
meat-eating hypothesis is this.

00:09:18.510 --> 00:09:21.710
That in the Pleiocene,
the australopithecines

00:09:21.710 --> 00:09:23.420
were not probably eating very much meat.

00:09:23.420 --> 00:09:27.720
But, chimpanzee-like style, they did hunt.

00:09:27.720 --> 00:09:30.700
And then that gave rise
to more meat-eating,

00:09:30.700 --> 00:09:32.400
in the habilene phase.

00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:35.100
And then meat-eating
became really critical.

00:09:35.100 --> 00:09:37.720
But we can dissect that and start asking

00:09:37.720 --> 00:09:40.470
are all of the questions
I've just been addressing

00:09:40.470 --> 00:09:43.410
and more about why this happened,

00:09:43.410 --> 00:09:45.620
and ultimately, what
its consequences were.

00:09:46.660 --> 00:09:49.160
So we're not gonna be talking
today about the consequences,

00:09:49.160 --> 00:09:50.920
we're gonna be talking more about

00:09:50.920 --> 00:09:53.710
why it happens and how it happens.

00:09:53.710 --> 00:09:56.360
And in thinking about where we come from,

00:09:56.360 --> 00:10:00.600
in relationship to where our
hunter-gatherer past took us,

00:10:00.600 --> 00:10:04.260
then we're gonna be taking
a third party as well,

00:10:04.260 --> 00:10:07.350
and bring chimps in, to
help us on that journey.

00:10:08.885 --> 00:10:12.662
(audience applauds)

00:10:12.662 --> 00:10:15.245
(bright music)

